---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="I'm Behind | Learn Web Design With Quinton Jason"
  description="A practical recovery path for ART 3020 students who are behind, organized around current project requirements and minimum viable progress."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">I'm Behind</p>
        <h1>Recover by getting one working version submitted.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          Being behind is stressful, but the path forward is usually smaller
          than it feels. Focus on the current project first, then improve once a
          working version exists.
        </p>
      </div>

      <section class="project-brief-section">
        <h2>If You Are Behind</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Focus on current project requirements first.</li>
          <li>Complete the lessons directly tied to that project.</li>
          <li>Skip optional content until caught up.</li>
          <li>Get a working version submitted.</li>
          <li>Improve afterward.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="project-brief-section">
        <h2>Minimum Viable Paths</h2>
        <div class="project-requirements">
          <article>
            <h3>If you're behind on Project 1</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/lessons/developer-environment-setup/">Developer Environment Setup</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/file-paths-and-site-structure/">File Paths</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/basic-html-structure-and-elements/">HTML Structure and Elements</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/intro-to-css/">CSS Basics</a></li>
            </ul>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>If you're behind on Project 2</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/lessons/website-process/">Website Process</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/flexbox/">Flexbox</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/responsive-web-design/">Responsive Web Design</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/html-forms-building-interactive-user-interfaces/">HTML Forms</a></li>
            </ul>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>If you're behind on Project 3</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/lessons/javascript-in-the-dom/">JavaScript in the DOM</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/css-transitions/">CSS Transitions</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/css-animation/">CSS Animation</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/gsap-web-animation/">GSAP Web Animation</a></li>
            </ul>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>If you're behind on Project 4</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/lessons/page-types-templates-and-navigation/">Page Types and Templates</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/item-listing-and-details/">Item Listing and Details</a></li>
              <li><a href="/lessons/mastering-carousels/">Carousels</a></li>
              <li><a href="/qa-checklist/">Final QA Checklist</a></li>
            </ul>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="callout">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Keep Moving</p>
          <h2>Submit a working version, then improve it.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          A simple working project is better than an ambitious broken project.
          Once the page loads, the links work, and the live URL updates, you can
          make it stronger.
        </p>
        <div class="button-row">
          <a class="button button--primary" href="/projects/">Open Projects</a>
          <a class="button" href="/debugging/">Common Fixes</a>
          <a class="button" href="/how-to-submit/">How To Submit</a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
